[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] In programming, **Types** are used to group similar values into categories.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] In Haskell, the type system is a powerful way of reducing the number of mistakes in your code.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Programming deals with different sorts of entities.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] That's certainly not a number, but it stands for an operation which we can do with two numbers – namely, addition.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Similarly, consider a program that asks you for your name and then greets you with a "Hello" message.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Neither your name nor the word Hello are numbers.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] We might refer to all words and sentences and so forth as text.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] It's normal in programming to use a slightly more esoteric word: *String*, which is short for "string of characters".
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Haskell has a rule that all type names have to begin with a capital letter.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] We shall adhere to this convention henceforth.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Databases illustrate clearly the concept of types.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] For example, say we had a table in a database to store details about a person's contacts; a kind of personal telephone book.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The fields in each entry contain values.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Sherlock is a value as is 99 Long Road Street Villestown as well as 655523.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Let's classify the values in this example in terms of types.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] "First Name" and "Last Name" contain text, so we say that the values are of type String.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] At first glance, we might classify address as a String.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] However, the semantics behind an innocent address are quite complex.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Many human conventions dictate how we interpret addresses.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] For example, if the beginning of the address text contains a number it is likely the number of the house.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] If not, then it's probably the name of the house – except if it starts with "PO Box", in which case it's just a postal box address and doesn't indicate where the person lives at all.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Each part of the address has its own meaning.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] In principle, we can indeed say that addresses are Strings, but that doesn't capture many important features of addresses.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] When we describe something as a String, all that we are saying is that it is a sequence of characters (letters, numbers, etc).
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Recognizing something as a specialized type is far more meaningful.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] If we know something is an Address, we instantly know much more about the piece of data – for instance, that we can interpret it using the "human conventions" that give meaning to addresses.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] We might also apply this rationale to the telephone numbers.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] We could specify a TelephoneNumber type.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Then, if we were to come across some arbitrary sequence of digits which happened to be of type TelephoneNumber we would have access to a lot more information than if it were just a Number – for instance, we could start looking for things such as area and country codes on the initial digits.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Another reason not to consider the telephone numbers as Numbers is that doing arithmetic with them makes no sense.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] What is the meaning and expected effect of, say, multiplying a TelephoneNumber by 100?
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] It would not allow calling anyone by phone.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Also, each digit comprising a telephone number is important; we cannot accept losing some of them by rounding or even by omitting leading zeros.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] How does it help us program well to describe and categorize things?
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Once we define a type, we can specify what we can or cannot do with it.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] That makes it far easier to manage larger programs and avoid errors.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Let's explore how types work using GHCi.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The type of any expression can be checked with `:type` (or shortened to `:t`) command.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The symbol `::`, which will appear in a couple other places, can be read as simply "is of type", and indicates a *type signature*.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] `:type` reveals that truth values in Haskell are of type `Bool`, as illustrated above for the two possible values, `True` and `False`, as well as for a sample expression that will evaluate to one of them.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Note that boolean values are not just for value comparisons.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] `Bool` captures the semantics of a yes/no answer, so it can represent any information of such kind – say, whether a name was found in a spreadsheet, or whether a user has toggled an on/off option.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Literal characters are entered by enclosing them with single quotation marks.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] So, literal character values have type `Char` (short for "character").
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] `[Char]` means a number of characters chained together, forming a *list* of characters.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Haskell considers all Strings to be lists of characters.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Lists in general are important entities in Haskell, and we will cover them in more detail in a little while.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Incidentally, Haskell allows for *type synonyms*, which work pretty much like synonyms in human languages (words that mean the same thing – say, 'big' and 'large').
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] In Haskell, type synonyms are alternative names for types.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] For instance, `String` is defined as a synonym of `[Char]`, and so we can freely substitute one with the other.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] is also perfectly valid, and in many cases a lot more readable.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] From here on we'll mostly refer to text values as `String`, rather than `[Char]`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] So far, we have seen how values (strings, booleans, characters, etc.) have types and how these types help us to categorize and describe them.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Now, the big twist that makes Haskell's type system truly powerful: *Functions* have types as well.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Let's look at some examples to see how that works.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] We can negate boolean values with `not` (e.g.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] `not True` evaluates to `False` and vice-versa).
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] To figure out the type of a function, we consider two things: the type of values it takes as its input and the type of value it returns.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] `not` takes a `Bool` (the `Bool` to be negated), and returns a `Bool` (the negated `Bool`).
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] You can read this as "`not` is a function from things of type `Bool` to things of type `Bool`".
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The description of a function's type is in terms of the types of argument(s) it takes and the type of value it evaluates to.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] At its lowest level, a computer only knows binary 1s and 0s.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] To represent text, every character is first converted to a number, then that number is converted to binary and stored.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] That's how a piece of text (which is just a sequence of characters) is encoded into binary.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Normally, we're only interested in how to encode characters into their numerical representations, because the computer takes care of the conversion to binary numbers without our intervention.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The easiest way to convert characters to numbers is simply to write all the possible characters down, then number them.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] For example, we might decide that 'a' corresponds to 1, then 'b' to 2, and so on.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] This is what something called the ASCII standard is: take 128 commonly-used characters and number them (ASCII doesn't actually start with 'a', but the general idea is the same).
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The new type on the signatures above, `Int`, refers to integer numbers, and is one of quite a few different types of numbers.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The type signature of `chr` tells us that it takes an argument of type `Int`, an integer number, and evaluates to a result of type Char.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The converse is the case with `ord`: It takes things of type Char and returns things of type Int.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] With the info from the type signatures, it becomes immediately clear which of the functions encodes a character into a numeric code (`ord`) and which does the decoding back to a character (`chr`).
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] To make things more concrete, here are a few examples.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Notice that the two functions aren't available by default; so before trying them in GHCi you need to use the `:module Data.Char` (or `:m Data.Char`) command to load the Data.Char module where they are defined.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] What would be the type of a function that takes more than one argument?
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The general technique for forming the type of a function that accepts more than one argument is simply to write down all the types of the arguments in a row, in order (so in this case `p` first then `q`), then link them all with `->`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Finally, add the type of the result to the end of the row and stick a final `->` in just before it.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Add in the result type and a final `->`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] In our case, we're just doing some basic boolean operations so the result remains a Bool.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] A library is a collection of common code used by many programs.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] As you'll learn in the Haskell in Practice section of the course, one popular group of Haskell libraries are the GUI (**G**raphical **U**ser **I**nterface) ones.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] These provide functions for dealing with the visual things computer users are familiar with: menus, buttons, application windows, moving the mouse around, etc.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] One function from one of these libraries is called `openWindow`, and you can use it to open a new window in your application.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] For example, say you're writing a word processor, and the user has clicked on the 'Options' button.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] You need to open a new window which contains all the options that they can change.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] You don't know these types, but they're quite simple.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] All three of the types there, `WindowTitle`, `WindowSize` and `Window` are defined by the GUI library that provides `openWindow`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] As we saw earlier, the two arrows mean that the first two types are the types of the parameters, and the last is the type of the result.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] `WindowTitle` holds the title of the window (which typically appears in a title bar at the very top of the window), and `WindowSize` specifies how big the window should be.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The function then returns a value of type Window which represents the actual window.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] So, even if you have never seen a function before or don't know how it actually works, a type signature can give you a general idea of what the function does.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Make a habit of testing every new function you meet with :t.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] If you start doing that now, you'll not only learn about the standard library Haskell functions but also develop a useful kind of intuition about functions in Haskell.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] We have explored the basic theory behind types and how they apply to Haskell.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Now, we will see how type signatures are used for annotating functions in source files.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] For maximum clarity, type signatures go above the corresponding function definition.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The signatures we add in this way serve a dual role: they clarify the type of the functions both to human readers and to the compiler/interpreter.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] If type signatures tell the interpreter (or compiler) about the function type, how did we write our earliest Haskell code without type signatures?
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Well, when you don't tell Haskell the types of your functions and variables it figures them out through a process called *type inference*.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] In essence, the compiler starts with the types of things it knows and then works out the types of the rest of the values.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] `isL` is a function that takes an argument `c` and returns the result of evaluating `c == 'l'`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Without a type signature, the type of `c` and the type of the result are not specified.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] In the expression `c == 'l'`, however, the compiler knows that `'l'` is a `Char`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Since `c` and `'l'` are being compared with equality with `(==)` and both arguments of `(==)` must have the same type, it follows that `c` must be a `Char`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Finally, since `isL c` is the result of `(==)` it must be a `Bool`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Indeed, if you leave out the type signature, the Haskell compiler will discover it through this process.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] You can verify that by using :t on `isL` with or without a signature.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] So why write type signatures if they will be inferred anyway?
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] In some cases, the compiler lacks information to infer the type, and so the signature becomes obligatory.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] In some other cases, we can use a type signature to influence to a certain extent the final type of a function or value.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] A somewhat more realistic example will help us understand better how signatures can help documentation.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The piece of code quoted below is a tiny *module* (modules are the typical way of preparing a library), and this way of organizing code is like that in the libraries bundled with GHC.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Do not go crazy trying to understand how the functions here actually work; that is beside the point as we still have not covered many of the features being used.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] This tiny library provides three string manipulation functions.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] `uppercase` converts a string to upper case, `lowercase` to lower case, and `capitalize` capitalizes the first letter of every word.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Each of these functions takes a `String` as argument and evaluates to another `String`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Even if we do not understand how these functions work, looking at the type signatures allows us to immediately know the types of the arguments and return values.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Paired with sensible function names, we have enough information to figure out how we can use the functions.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Note that when functions have the same type we have the option of writing just one signature for all of them, by separating their names with commas, as above with `uppercase` and `lowercase`.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The role of types in preventing errors is central to typed languages.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] When passing expressions around you have to make sure the types match up like they did here.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] If they don't, you'll get *type errors* when you try to compile; your program won't pass the *typecheck*.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] This helps reduce bugs in your programs.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] That line will cause a program to fail when compiling.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] An easy typo to make, but Haskell catches the error when you tried to compile.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] You don't have to wait until you run the program for the bug to become apparent.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Updating a program commonly involves changes to types.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] If a change is unintended, or has unforeseen consequences, then it will show up when compiling.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Haskell programmers often remark that once they have fixed all the type errors, and their programs compile, that they tend to "just work".
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] The behavior may not always match the intention, but the program won't crash.
[src:haskell/haskell-type-basics] Haskell has far fewer *run-time errors* (where your program goes wrong when you run it rather than when you compile) than other languages.
[src:haskell/haskell] Haskell's semantics are historically based on those of the Miranda programming language, which served to focus the efforts of the initial Haskell working group.
[src:haskell/haskell] The last formal specification of the language was made in July 2010, while the development of GHC continues to expand Haskell via language extensions.
[src:haskell/haskell] Haskell is used in academia and industry.
[src:haskell/haskell] As of May 2021, Haskell was the 28th most popular programming language by Google searches for tutorials, and made up less than 1% of active users on the GitHub source code repository.
[src:haskell/haskell] After the release of Miranda by Research Software Ltd. in 1985, interest in lazy functional languages grew.
[src:haskell/haskell] By 1987, more than a dozen non-strict, purely functional programming languages existed.
[src:haskell/haskell] Miranda was the most widely used, but it was proprietary software.
[src:haskell/haskell] At the conference on Functional Programming Languages and Computer Architecture (FPCA '87) in Portland, Oregon, there was a strong consensus that a committee be formed to define an open standard for such languages.
[src:haskell/haskell] The committee's purpose was to consolidate existing functional languages into a common one to serve as a basis for future research in functional-language design.
[src:haskell/haskell] Haskell was developed by a committee, attempting to bring together off-the-shelf solutions where possible.
[src:haskell/haskell] Type classes were first proposed by Philip Wadler and Stephen Blott to address the ad hoc handling of equality types and arithmetic overloading in languages at the time.
[src:haskell/haskell] In early versions of Haskell up until and including version 1.2, user interaction and input/output (IO) were handled by both streams-based and continuation-based mechanisms, which were widely considered unsatisfactory.
[src:haskell/haskell] In version 1.3, monadic IO was introduced, along with the generalisation of type classes to higher kinds (type constructors).
[src:haskell/haskell] Along with "do notation", which provides syntactic sugar for the `Monad` type class, this gave Haskell an effect system that maintained referential transparency and was convenient.
[src:haskell/haskell] Another notable change in early versions was the moving of the "sequential evaluation" operation `seq` (which creates a data dependency between values, and is used in lazy languages to avoid excessive memory consumption) from a type class to a standard function to make refactoring more practical.
[src:haskell/haskell] The first version of Haskell ("Haskell 1.0") was defined in 1990.
[src:haskell/haskell] The committee's efforts resulted in a series of language definitions (1.0, 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, and 1.4).
[src:haskell/haskell] In late 1997, the series culminated in *Haskell 98*, intended to specify a stable, minimal, portable version of the language and an accompanying standard library for teaching, and as a base for future extensions.
[src:haskell/haskell] The committee expressly welcomed creating extensions and variants of Haskell 98 via adding and incorporating experimental features.
[src:haskell/haskell] In February 1999, the Haskell 98 language standard was originally published as *The Haskell 98 Report*.
[src:haskell/haskell] In January 2003, a revised version was published as *Haskell 98 Language and Libraries: The Revised Report*.
[src:haskell/haskell] The language continues to evolve rapidly, with the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) implementation representing the current *de facto* standard.
[src:haskell/haskell] In early 2006, the process of defining a successor to the Haskell 98 standard, informally named *Haskell Prime*, began.
[src:haskell/haskell] This was intended to be an ongoing incremental process to revise the language definition, producing a new revision up to once per year.
[src:haskell/haskell] The first revision, named *Haskell 2010*, was announced in November 2009 and published in July 2010.
[src:haskell/haskell] Haskell 2010 added several well-used and uncontroversial features previously enabled via compiler-specific flags.
[src:haskell/haskell] The next formal specification had been planned for 2020.
[src:haskell/haskell] On 29 October 2021, with GHC version 9.2.1, the GHC2021 extension was released.
[src:haskell/haskell] While this is not a formal language spec, it combines several stable, widely used GHC extensions to Haskell 2010.
[src:haskell/haskell] Haskell features lazy evaluation, lambda expressions, pattern matching, list comprehension, type classes and type polymorphism.
[src:haskell/haskell] It is a purely functional programming language, which means that functions generally have no side effects.
[src:haskell/haskell] A distinct construct exists to represent side effects, orthogonal to the type of functions.
[src:haskell/haskell] A pure function can return a side effect that is subsequently executed, modeling the impure functions of other languages.
[src:haskell/haskell] Haskell has a strong, static type system based on Hindley–Milner type inference.
[src:haskell/haskell] Its principal innovation in this area is type classes, originally conceived as a principled way to add overloading to the language, but since finding many more uses.
[src:haskell/haskell] The construct that represents side effects is an example of a monad: a general framework which can model various computations such as error handling, nondeterminism, parsing and software transactional memory.
[src:haskell/haskell] They are defined as ordinary datatypes, but Haskell provides some syntactic sugar for their use.
[src:haskell/haskell] Haskell has an open, published specification, and multiple implementations exist.
[src:haskell/haskell] Its main implementation, the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC), is both an interpreter and native-code compiler that runs on most platforms.
[src:haskell/haskell] GHC is noted for its rich type system incorporating recent innovations such as generalized algebraic data types and type families.
[src:haskell/haskell] The Computer Language Benchmarks Game also highlights its high-performance implementation of concurrency and parallelism.
[src:haskell/haskell] An active, growing community exists around the language, and more than 5,400 third-party open-source libraries and tools are available in the online package repository *Hackage*.
[src:haskell/haskell] Using Haskell's Fixed-point combinator allows this function to be written without any explicit recursion.
[src:haskell/haskell] As the *Integer* type has arbitrary-precision, this code will compute values such as `factorial 100000` (a 456,574-digit number), with no loss of precision.
[src:haskell/haskell] All listed implementations are distributed under open source licenses.
[src:haskell/haskell] Jan-Willem Maessen, in 2002, and Simon Peyton Jones, in 2003, discussed problems associated with lazy evaluation while also acknowledging the theoretical motives for it.
[src:haskell/haskell] In addition to purely practical considerations such as improved performance, they note that lazy evaluation makes it more difficult for programmers to reason about the performance of their code (particularly its space use).
[src:haskell/haskell] In particular it disables type classes by default.
[src:haskell/haskell] Ben Lippmeier designed Disciple as a strict-by-default (lazy by explicit annotation) dialect of Haskell with a type-and-effect system, to address Haskell's difficulties in reasoning about lazy evaluation and in using traditional data structures such as mutable arrays.
[src:haskell/haskell] Robert Harper, one of the authors of Standard ML, has given his reasons for not using Haskell to teach introductory programming.
[src:haskell/haskell] Among these are the difficulty of reasoning about resource use with non-strict evaluation, that lazy evaluation complicates the definition of datatypes and inductive reasoning, and the "inferiority" of Haskell's (old) class system compared to ML's module system.
[src:haskell/haskell] Haskell's build tool, Cabal, has historically been criticized for poorly handling multiple versions of the same library, a problem known as "Cabal hell".
[src:haskell/haskell] The Stackage server and Stack build tool were made in response to these criticisms.
[src:haskell/haskell] Cabal has since addressed this problem by borrowing ideas from the package manager Nix, with the new approach becoming the default in 2019.
[src:haskell/haskell] Clean is a close, slightly older relative of Haskell.
[src:haskell/haskell] Its biggest deviation from Haskell is in the use of uniqueness types instead of monads for input/output (I/O) and side effects.
[src:haskell/haskell] Haskell events have been regularly held concurrent with the International Conference on Functional Programming (ICFP) including workshops such as the Haskell Symposium (formerly the Haskell Workshop) and Commercial Users of Functional Programming.
[src:haskell/haskell] Other events include the Haskell Implementors Workshop, ZuriHac in Zurich, and Hac: The Haskell Hackathon.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] At the heart of functional programming is the idea that functions are *just like any other value*.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] The power of functional style comes from handling functions themselves as regular values, i.e. by passing functions to other functions and returning them from functions.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] A function that takes another function (or several functions) as an argument is called a *higher-order function*.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] They can be found pretty much anywhere in a Haskell program, and indeed we have already met some of them, such as `map` and the various folds.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] We saw commonplace examples of higher-order functions when discussing `map` in Lists II.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Now, we are going to explore some common ways of writing code that manipulates functions.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] For a concrete example, we will consider the task of sorting a list.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] *Quicksort* is a well-known recursive sorting algorithm.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] To apply its sorting strategy to a list, we first choose one element and then divide the rest of the list into (A) those elements that should go before the chosen element, (B) those elements equal to the chosen one, and (C) those that should go after.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Then, we apply the same algorithm to the unsorted (A) and (C) lists.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] After enough recursive sorting, we concatenate everything back together and have a final sorted list.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] That strategy can be translated into a Haskell implementation in a very simple way.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] It should be pointed out that our `quickSort` is rather naïve.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] A more efficient implementation would avoid the three passes through `filter` at each recursive step and not use `(++)` to build the sorted list.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Furthermore, unlike our implementation, the *original* quicksort algorithm does the sorting in-place using mutability.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] We will ignore such concerns for now, as we are more interested in the usage patterns of sorting functions, rather than in exact implementation.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Almost all the basic data types in Haskell are members of the `Ord` class, which is for ordering tests what `Eq` is for equality tests.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] The `Ord` class defines which ordering is the "natural" one for a given type.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `compare` takes two values and compares them, returning an `Ordering` value, which is `LT` if the first value is *less than* the second, `EQ` if it is *equal* and `GT` if it is *greater than*.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] For an `Ord` type, `(<)`, `(==)` from `Eq` and `(>)` can be seen as shortcuts to `compare` that check for one of the three possibilities and return a `Bool` to indicate whether the specified ordering is true according to the `Ord` specification for that type.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Note that each of the tests we use with `filter` in the definition of `quickSort` corresponds to one of the possible results of `compare`, and so we might have written, for instance, `less` as less = filter (\y -> y `compare` x == LT) xs.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] With `quickSort`, sorting any list with elements in the `Ord` class is easy.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Suppose we have a list of `String` and we want to sort them; we just apply `quickSort` to the list.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] As you can see, capitalization is considered for sorting by default.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Haskell `String`s are lists of Unicode characters.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Unicode (and almost all other encodings of characters) specifies that the character code for capital letters are less than the lower case letters.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] To get a proper dictionary-like sorting, we need a case insensitive `quickSort`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] To achieve that, we can take a hint from the discussion of `compare` just above.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] While this version is less tidy than the original one, it makes it obvious that the ordering of the elements hinges entirely on the `compare` function.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] That means we only need to replace `compare` with an `(Ord a) => a -> a -> Ordering` function of our choice.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Therefore, our updated `quickSort'` is a higher-order function which takes a comparison function along with the list to sort.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] We can reuse our `quickSort'` function to serve many different purposes.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] If we wanted a *descending* order, we could just reverse our original sorted list with `reverse (quickSort dictionary)`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Yet to actually do the initial sort descending, we could supply `quickSort'` with a comparison function that returns the opposite of the usual `Ordering`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `Data.List` offers a `sort` function for sorting lists.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] It does not use quicksort; rather, it uses an efficient implementation of an algorithm called *mergesort*.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] The concept of *currying* (the generating of intermediate functions on the way toward a final result) was first introduced in the earlier chapter "Lists II".
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] This is a good place to revisit how currying works.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Most of the time, the type of a higher-order function provides a guideline about how to use it.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] A straightforward way of reading the type signature would be "`quickSort'` takes, as its first argument, a function that gives an ordering of two `a`s.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Finally, it returns a new list of `a`s".
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] This is enough to correctly guess that it uses the given ordering function to sort the list.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Note that the parentheses surrounding `a -> a -> Ordering` are mandatory.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] They specify that `a -> a -> Ordering` forms a single argument that happens to be a function.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Without the parentheses, we would get `a -> a -> Ordering -> [a] -> [a]` which accepts four arguments (none of which are themselves functions) instead of the desired two, and that wouldn't work as desired.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Remember that the `->` operator is right-associative.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Thus, our erroneous type signature `a -> a -> Ordering -> [a] -> [a]` means the same thing as `a -> (a -> (Ordering -> ([a] -> [a])))`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Given that `->` is right-associative, the explicitly grouped version of the correct `quickSort'` signature is actually `(a -> a -> Ordering) -> ([a] -> [a])`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Our original `quickSort` lacking the adjustable comparison function argument was of type `[a] -> [a]`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Our new `quickSort'` is simply a function that generates `quickSort` style functions!
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] If we plug in `compare` for the `(a -> a -> Ordering)` part, then we just return our original simple `quickSort` function.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] If we use a different comparison function for the argument, we generate a *different* variety of a `quickSort` function.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Of course, if we not only give a comparison function as an argument but also feed in an actual list to sort, then the final result is not the new `quickSort`-style function; instead, it continues on and passes the list to the new function and returns the sorted list as our final result.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] We will close the chapter by discussing a few examples of common and useful general-purpose higher-order functions.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Familiarity with these will greatly enhance your skill at both writing and reading Haskell code.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `flip` is a handy little Prelude function.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] It takes a function of two arguments and returns a version of the same function with the arguments swapped.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `flip` is particularly useful when we want to pass a function with two arguments of different types to another function and the arguments are in the wrong order with respect to the signature of the higher-order function.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] The `(.)` composition operator is another higher-order function.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `(.)` takes two functions as arguments and returns a new function which applies the second function to the argument and then the first.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Composition and higher-order functions provide a range of powerful tricks.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] For a tiny sample, first consider the `inits` function, defined in the module `Data.List`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Swallowing a definition so condensed may look daunting at first, so analyze it slowly, bit by bit, recalling what each function does and using the type signatures as a guide.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] The definition of `myInits` is super concise and clean with use of parentheses kept to a bare minimum.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Naturally, if one goes overboard with composition by writing mile-long `(.)` chains, things will get confusing; but, when deployed reasonably, these point-free styles shine.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Furthermore, the implementation is quite "high level": we do not deal explicitly with details like pattern matching or recursion; the functions we deployed — both the higher-order ones and their functional arguments — take care of such plumbing.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `($)` is a curious higher-order operator.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] It takes a function as its first argument, and *all* it does is to apply the function to the second argument, so that, for instance, `(head $ "abc") == (head "abc")`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] You might think that `($)` is completely useless!
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] However, there are two interesting points about it.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] First, `($)` has very low precedence, unlike regular function application which has the highest precedence.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] In effect, that means we can avoid confusing nesting of parentheses by breaking precedence with `$`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] As the name suggests, `uncurry` is a function that undoes currying; that is, it converts a function of two arguments into a function that takes a pair as its only argument.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] One interesting use of `uncurry` occasionally seen in the wild is in combination with `($)`, so that the first element of a pair is applied to the second.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] There is also `curry`, which is the opposite of `uncurry`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Because most Haskell functions are already curried, `curry` is nowhere near as common as `uncurry`.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Finally, we should mention two functions which, while not higher-order functions themselves, are most often used as arguments to higher-order functions.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `id`, the *identity* function, is a function with type `a -> a` that returns its argument unchanged.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `const` takes two arguments, discards the second and returns the first.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] Seen as a function of one argument, `a -> (b -> a)`, it returns a constant function, which always returns the same value no matter what argument it is given.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `id` and `const` might appear worthless at first.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] However, when dealing with higher-order functions it is sometimes necessary to pass a dummy function, be it one that does nothing with its argument or one that always returns the same value.
[src:haskell/higher-order-functions] `id` and `const` give us convenient dummy functions for such cases.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Haskell uses two fundamental structures for managing several values: lists and tuples.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] They both work by grouping multiple values into a single combined value.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The square brackets delimit the list, and individual elements are separated by commas.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The only important restriction is that all elements in a list must be of the same type.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] In addition to specifying the whole list at once using square brackets and commas, you can build them up piece by piece using the `(:)` operator pronounced "cons".
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The process of building up a list this way is often referred to as **consing**.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] This terminology comes from LISP programmers who invented the verb "to cons" (a mnemonic for "constructor") to refer to this specific task of prepending an element to a list.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] When you cons something on to a list (`something:someList`), you get back another list.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Thus, you can keep on consing for as long as you wish.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Note that the cons operator evaluates from right to left.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Another (more general) way to think of it is that it takes the first value to its left and the whole expression to its right.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] In fact, Haskell builds all lists this way by consing all elements to the *empty list*, `[]`.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The commas-and-brackets notation are just *syntactic sugar*.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] You will, however, want to watch out for a potential pitfall in list construction.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] `True:False` produces a familiar-looking type error message.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] It tells us that the cons operator `(:)` (which is really just a function) expected a list as its second argument, but we gave it another `Bool` instead.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] `(:)` only knows how to stick things onto lists.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] As we briefly mentioned in the Type Basics module, strings in Haskell are just lists of characters.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] That means values of type String can be manipulated just like any other list.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] For instance, instead of entering strings directly as a sequence of characters enclosed in double quotation marks, they may also be constructed through a sequence of Char values, either linked with `(:)` and terminated by an empty list or using the commas-and-brackets notation.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Using double-quoted strings is just more syntactic sugar.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Lists can contain *anything* — as long as they are all of the same type.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Because lists are things too, lists can contain other lists!
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Lists of lists can be tricky sometimes because a list of things does not have the same type as a thing all by itself.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The type `Int` is different from `[Int]`.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Lists of different types of things cannot be consed, but the empty list can be consed with lists of anything.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Lists of lists allow us to express some kinds of complicated, structured data (two-dimensional matrices, for example).
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] They are also one of the places where the Haskell type system truly shines.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Human programmers (including this wikibook co-author) get confused *all* the time when working with lists of lists, and having restrictions on types often helps in wading through the potential mess.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Tuples are marked by parentheses with elements delimited by commas.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The first example is a tuple containing two elements: True and 1.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The next example again has two elements: "Hello world" and False.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The third example is a tuple consisting of *five* elements: 4 (a number), 5 (another number), "Six" (a string), True (a boolean value), and 'b' (a character).
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] A quick note on nomenclature: In general you use *n-tuple* to denote a tuple of size *n*.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Commonly, we call 2-tuples (that is, tuples with 2 elements) *pairs* and 3-tuples *triples*.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Tuples of greater sizes aren't actually all that common, but we can logically extend the naming system to *quadruples*, *quintuples*, and so on.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Tuples are handy when you want to return more than one value from a function.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] In many languages, returning two or more things at once often requires wrapping them up in a single-purpose data structure, maybe one that only gets used in that function.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] In Haskell, we would return such results as a tuple.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] We can apply the same reasoning to tuples about storing lists within lists.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Tuples are things too, so you can store tuples within tuples (within tuples up to any arbitrary level of complexity).
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Likewise, you could also have lists of tuples, tuples of lists, and all sorts of related combinations.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The type of a tuple is defined not only by its size, but, like lists, by the types of objects it contains.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] For example, the tuples `("Hello",32)` and `(47,"World")` are fundamentally different.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] One is of type `(String,Int)`, whereas the other is `(Int,String)`.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] This has implications for building up lists of tuples.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] For lists and tuples to be useful, we will need to access the internal values they contain.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] 2-tuples) representing the (*x*, *y*) coordinates of a point.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Imagine you want to specify a specific square on a chess board.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] You could label the ranks and files from 1 to 8.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Then, a pair `(2, 5)` could represent the square in rank 2 and file 5.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Say we want a function for finding all the pieces in a given rank.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] We could start with the coordinates of all the pieces and then look at the rank part and see whether it equals whatever row we want to examine.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Given a coordinate pair `(x, y)` of a piece, our function would need to extract the `x` (the rank coordinate).
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] For this sort of goal, there are two standard functions, `fst` and `snd`, that retrieve the first and second elements out of a pair, respectively.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Note that these functions, by definition, *only* work on pairs.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] For lists, the functions `head` and `tail` are *roughly* analogous to `fst` and `snd`.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] They disassemble a list by taking apart what `(:)` joined.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] `head` evaluates to the first element of the list, while `tail` gives the rest of the list.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Unfortunately, we have a serious problem with `head` and `tail`.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] If we apply either of them to an empty list...
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] ... it blows up, as an empty list has no first element, nor any other elements at all.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Outside of GHCi, attempting to run `head` or `tail` on the empty list will crash a program.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] We will play with `head` and `tail` for the moment, but we want to avoid any risk of such malfunctions in our real code, so we will learn later about better options.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Using `head` and `tail` works fine if we are careful and never pass them an empty list, or if we somehow test whether a list is empty before calling them." But that way lies madness.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] As programs get bigger and more complicated, the number of places in which an empty list could end up being passed to `head` and `tail` grows quickly as does the number of places in which we might make a mistake.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] As a rule of thumb, you should avoid functions that might fail without warning.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] As we advance through the book, we will learn better ways to avoid these risks.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The four functions introduced here do not appear to fully solve the problem we started this section with.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] While `fst` and `snd` provide a satisfactory solution for pairs, what about tuples with three or more elements?
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] And with lists, can we do any better than just breaking them after the first element?
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] For the moment, we will have to leave these questions pending.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Once we do some necessary groundwork, we will return to this subject in future chapters on list manipulation.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] For now, know that separating head and tail of a list will allow us to do anything we want.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Lists of `Bool` are a different type than lists of `[Char]` (which is the same as a list of `String` because `[Char]` and `String` are synonyms).
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Since functions only accept arguments of the types specified in the type of the function, that might lead to some complications.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] For example, consider the case of `head`.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] After all, lists are assembled in the same way regardless of the types of the values they contain, and so we would expect the procedure to get the first element of the list would remain the same in all cases.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The `a` in the signature is *not* a type – remember that type names always start with uppercase letters.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] When Haskell sees a type variable, it allows any type to take its place.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] In type theory (a branch of mathematics), this is called *polymorphism*: functions or values with only a single type are called *monomorphic*, and things that use type variables to admit more than one type are *polymorphic*.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The type of `head`, for instance, tells us that it takes a list (`[a]`) of values of an arbitrary type (`a`) and gives back a value of that same type (`a`).
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Note that within a single type signature, all cases of the same type variable must be of the same type.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] which means that `f` takes an argument of *any* type and gives a result of *any* type which *may or may not* match the type of whatever we have for `a`.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] The different type variables do not specify that the types must be different, it only says that they can be different.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] As we saw, you can use the `fst` and `snd` functions to extract parts of pairs.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] By now, you should already be building the habit of wondering "what type is this?" for every function you come across.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Let's consider the cases of `fst` and `snd`.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] These two functions take a pair as their argument and return one element of this pair.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] As with lists, the type of a pair depends on the type of its elements, so the functions need to be polymorphic.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Also remember that pairs (and tuples in general) don't have to be homogeneous with respect to internal types.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] That would mean `fst` would only work if the first and second part of the pair given as input had the same type.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] If you knew nothing about `fst` and `snd` other than the type signatures, you might still guess that they return the first and second parts of a pair, respectively.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Although that is correct, other functions may have this same type signature.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] All the signatures say is that they just have to return something *with the same type* as the first and second parts of the pair, respectively.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] This chapter introduced lists and tuples.
[src:haskell/lists-and-tuples] Lists and tuples can be combined in any number of ways: lists within lists, tuples within lists, etc, but their criteria must still be fulfilled for the combinations to be valid.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In functional programming, **monads** are a way to structure computations as a sequence of steps, where each step not only produces a value but also some extra information about the computation, such as a potential failure, non-determinism, or side effect.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] More formally, a monad is a type constructor M equipped with two operations, `return : <A>(a : A) -> M(A)` which lifts a value into the monadic context, and `bind : <A,B>(m_a : M(A), f : A -> M(B)) -> M(B)` which chains monadic computations.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In simpler terms, monads can be thought of as interfaces implemented on type constructors, that allow for functions to abstract over various type constructor variants that implement monad (e.g.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Both the concept of a monad and the term originally come from category theory, where a monad is defined as an endofunctor with additional structure.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Research beginning in the late 1980s and early 1990s established that monads could bring seemingly disparate computer-science problems under a unified, functional model.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Category theory also provides a few formal requirements, known as the **monad laws**, which should be satisfied by any monad and can be used to verify monadic code.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Since monads make semantics explicit for a kind of computation, they can also be used to implement convenient language features.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Some languages, such as Haskell, even offer pre-built definitions in their core libraries for the general monad structure and common instances.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] "For a monad `m`, a value of type `m a` represents having access to a value of type `a` within the context of the monad." —C.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] More exactly, a monad can be used where unrestricted access to a value is inappropriate for reasons specific to the scenario.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In the case of the Maybe monad, it is because the value may not exist.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In the case of the IO monad, it is because the value may not be known yet, such as when the monad represents user input that will only be provided after a prompt is displayed.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In all cases the scenarios in which access makes sense are captured by the bind operation defined for the monad; for the Maybe monad a value is bound only if it exists, and for the IO monad a value is bound only after the previous operations in the sequence have been performed.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] With these elements, the programmer composes a sequence of function calls (a "pipeline") with several *bind* operators chained together in an expression.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Each function call transforms its input plain-type value, and the bind operator handles the returned monadic value, which is fed into the next step in the sequence.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Typically, the bind operator `>>=` may contain code unique to the monad that performs additional computation steps not available in the function received as a parameter.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Between each pair of composed function calls, the bind operator can inject into the monadic value `m a` some additional information that is not accessible within the function `f`, and pass it along down the pipeline.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] It can also exert finer control of the flow of execution, for example by calling the function only under some conditions, or executing the function calls in a particular order.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] One example of a monad is the `Maybe` type.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Undefined null results are one particular pain point that many procedural languages don't provide specific tools for dealing with, requiring use of the null object pattern or checks to test for invalid values at each operation to handle undefined values.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] This causes bugs and makes it harder to build robust software that gracefully handles errors.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The `Maybe` type forces the programmer to deal with these potentially undefined results by explicitly defining the two states of a result: `Just ⌑result⌑`, or `Nothing`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] For example, the programmer might be constructing a parser, which is to return an intermediate result, or else signal a condition which the parser has detected, and which the programmer must also handle.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] With just a little extra functional spice on top, this `Maybe` type transforms into a fully-featured monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In most languages, the Maybe monad is also known as an option type, which is just a type that marks whether or not it contains a value.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Typically they are expressed as some kind of enumerated type.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In the Rust programming language it is called `Option<T>` and variants of this type can either be a value of generic type `T`, or the empty variant: `None`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] `Option<T>` can also be understood as a "wrapping" type, and this is where its connection to monads comes in.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In languages with some form of the Maybe type, there are functions that aid in their use such as composing **monadic functions** with each other and testing if a Maybe contains a value.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In the following hard-coded example, a Maybe type is used as a result of functions that may fail, in this case the type returns nothing if there is a divide-by-zero.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] One such way to test whether or not a Maybe contains a value is to use `if` statements.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Monads can compose functions that return Maybe, putting them together.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Instead of repeating `Some` expressions, we can use something called a *bind* operator.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] (also known as "map", "flatmap", or "shove").
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] This operation takes a monad and a function that returns a monad and runs the function on the inner value of the passed monad, returning the monad from the function.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In Haskell, there is an operator *bind*, or (`>>=`) that allows for this monadic composition in a more elegant form similar to function composition.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] With `>>=` available, `chainable_division` can be expressed much more succinctly with the help of anonymous functions (i.e. lambdas).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Notice in the expression below how the two nested lambdas each operate on the wrapped value in the passed `Maybe` monad using the bind operator.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] What has been shown so far is basically a monad, but to be more concise, the following is a strict list of qualities necessary for a monad as defined by the following section.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] These are the 3 things necessary to form a monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Other monads may embody different logical processes, and some may have additional properties, but all of them will have these three similar components.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The more common definition for a monad in functional programming, used in the above example, is actually based on a Kleisli triple ⟨T, η, μ⟩ rather than category theory's standard definition.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The two constructs turn out to be mathematically equivalent, however, so either definition will yield a valid monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Algebraically, this means any monad both gives rise to a category (called the Kleisli category) *and* a monoid in the category of functors (from values to computations), with monadic composition as a binary operator in the monoid and unit as identity in the monoid.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The value of the monad pattern goes beyond merely condensing code and providing a link to mathematical reasoning.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Whatever language or default programming paradigm a developer uses, following the monad pattern brings many of the benefits of purely functional programming.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] By reifying a specific kind of computation, a monad not only encapsulates the tedious details of that computational pattern, but it does so in a declarative way, improving the code's clarity.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] As monadic values explicitly represent not only computed values, but computed *effects*, a monadic expression can be replaced with its value in referentially transparent positions, much like pure expressions can be, allowing for many techniques and optimizations based on rewriting.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Typically, programmers will use bind to chain monadic functions into a sequence, which has led some to describe monads as "programmable semicolons", a reference to how many imperative languages use semicolons to separate statements.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] However, monads do not actually order computations; even in languages that use them as central features, simpler function composition can arrange steps within a program.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] A monad's general utility rather lies in simplifying a program's structure and improving separation of concerns through abstraction.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The monad structure can also be seen as a uniquely mathematical and compile time variation on the decorator pattern.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Some monads can pass along extra data that is inaccessible to functions, and some even exert finer control over execution, for example only calling a function under certain conditions.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Because they let application programmers implement domain logic while offloading boilerplate code onto pre-developed modules, monads can even be considered a tool for aspect-oriented programming.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] One other noteworthy use for monads is isolating side-effects, like input/output or mutable state, in otherwise purely functional code.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Even purely functional languages *can* still implement these "impure" computations without monads, via an intricate mix of function composition and continuation-passing style (CPS) in particular.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] With monads though, much of this scaffolding can be abstracted away, essentially by taking each recurring pattern in CPS code and bundling it into a distinct monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] If a language does not support monads by default, it is still possible to implement the pattern, often without much difficulty.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] When translated from category-theory to programming terms, the monad structure is a generic concept and can be defined directly in any language that supports an equivalent feature for bounded polymorphism.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] A concept's ability to remain agnostic about operational details while working on underlying types is powerful, but the unique features and stringent behavior of monads set them apart from other concepts.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Discussions of specific monads will typically focus on solving a narrow implementation problem since a given monad represents a specific computational form.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In some situations though, an application can even meet its high-level goals by using appropriate monads within its core logic.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The term "monad" in programming dates to the APL and J programming languages, which do tend toward being purely functional.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] However, in those languages, "monad" is only shorthand for a function taking one parameter (a function with two parameters being a "dyad", and so on).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The mathematician Roger Godement was the first to formulate the concept of a monad (dubbing it a "standard construction") in the late 1950s, though the term "monad" that came to dominate was popularized by category-theorist Saunders Mac Lane.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The form defined above using bind, however, was originally described in 1965 by mathematician Heinrich Kleisli in order to prove that any monad could be characterized as an adjunction between two (covariant) functors.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Starting in the 1980s, a vague notion of the monad pattern began to surface in the computer science community.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] According to programming language researcher Philip Wadler, computer scientist John C.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Reynolds anticipated several facets of it in the 1970s and early 1980s, when he discussed the value of continuation-passing style, of category theory as a rich source for formal semantics, and of the type distinction between values and computations.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The research language Opal, which was actively designed up until 1990, also effectively based I/O on a monadic type, but the connection was not realized at the time.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The computer scientist Eugenio Moggi was the first to explicitly link the monad of category theory to functional programming, in a conference paper in 1989, followed by a more refined journal submission in 1991.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In earlier work, several computer scientists had advanced using category theory to provide semantics for the lambda calculus.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Moggi's key insight was that a real-world program is not just a function from values to other values, but rather a transformation that forms *computations* on those values.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] When formalized in category-theoretic terms, this leads to the conclusion that monads are the structure to represent these computations.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Several others popularized and built on this idea, including Philip Wadler and Simon Peyton Jones, both of whom were involved in the specification of Haskell.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In particular, Haskell used a problematic "lazy stream" model up through v1.2 to reconcile I/O with lazy evaluation, until switching over to a more flexible monadic interface.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The Haskell community would go on to apply monads to many problems in functional programming, and in the 2010s, researchers working with Haskell eventually recognized that monads are applicative functors; and that both monads and arrows are monoids.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] At first, programming with monads was largely confined to Haskell and its derivatives, but as functional programming has influenced other paradigms, many languages have incorporated a monad pattern (in spirit if not in name).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Formulations now exist in Scheme, Perl, Python, Racket, Clojure, Scala, F#, and have also been considered for a new ML standard.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] One benefit of the monad pattern is bringing mathematical precision on the composition of computations.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Not only can the monad laws be used to check an instance's validity, but features from related structures (like functors) can be used through subtyping.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Returning to the `Maybe` example, its components were declared to make up a monad, but no proof was given that it satisfies the monad laws.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Though rarer in computer science, one can use category theory directly, which defines a monad as a functor with two additional natural transformations.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] This is not always a major issue, however, especially when a monad is derived from a pre-existing functor, whereupon the monad inherits map automatically.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] A monad's first transformation is actually the same unit from the Kleisli triple, but following the hierarchy of structures closely, it turns out unit characterizes an applicative functor, an intermediate structure between a monad and a basic functor.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In the applicative context, unit is sometimes referred to as **pure** but is still the same function.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The **List monad** naturally demonstrates how deriving a monad from a simpler functor can come in handy.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] In many languages, a list structure comes pre-defined along with some basic features, so a `List` type constructor and append operator (represented with `++` for infix notation) are assumed as already given here.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] From here, applying a function iteratively with a list comprehension may seem like an easy choice for bind and converting lists to a full monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The difficulty with this approach is that bind expects monadic functions, which in this case will output lists themselves; as more functions are applied, layers of nested lists will accumulate, requiring more than a basic comprehension.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Now, these two procedures already promote `List` to an applicative functor.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] One application for this monadic list is representing nondeterministic computation.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] `List` can hold results for all execution paths in an algorithm, then condense itself at each step to "forget" which paths led to which results (a sometimes important distinction from deterministic, exhaustive algorithms).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Another benefit is that checks can be embedded in the monad; specific paths can be pruned transparently at their first point of failure, with no need to rewrite functions in the pipeline.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] A second situation where `List` shines is composing multivalued functions.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] For instance, the nth complex root of a number should yield n distinct complex numbers, but if another mth root is then taken of those results, the final m•n values should be identical to the output of the m•nth root.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] `List` completely automates this issue away, condensing the results from each step into a flat, mathematically correct list.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Monads present opportunities for interesting techniques beyond just organizing program logic.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Monads can lay the groundwork for useful syntactic features while their high-level and mathematical nature enable significant abstraction.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Although using bind openly often makes sense, many programmers prefer a syntax that mimics imperative statements (called *do-notation* in Haskell, *perform-notation* in OCaml, *computation expressions* in F#, and *for comprehension* in Scala).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] This is only syntactic sugar that disguises a monadic pipeline as a code block; the compiler will then quietly translate these expressions into underlying functional code.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Translating the `add` function from the `Maybe` into Haskell can show this feature in action.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] A second example shows how `Maybe` can be used in an entirely different language: F#.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Every monad needs a specific implementation that meets the monad laws, but other aspects like the relation to other structures or standard idioms within a language are shared by all monads.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] As a result, a language or library may provide a general `Monad` interface with function prototypes, subtyping relationships, and other general facts.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Besides providing a head-start to development and guaranteeing a new monad inherits features from a supertype (such as functors), checking a monad's design against the interface adds another layer of quality control.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] Monadic code can often be simplified even further through the judicious use of operators.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The map functional can be especially helpful since it works on more than just ad-hoc monadic functions; so long as a monadic function should work analogously to a predefined operator, map can be used to instantly "lift" the simpler operator into a monadic one.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] The process could be taken even one step further by defining `add` not just for `Maybe`, but for the whole `Monad` interface.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p01] By doing this, any new monad that matches the structure interface and implements its own map will immediately inherit a lifted version of `add` too.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] `Identity` does actually have valid uses though, such as providing a base case for recursive monad transformers.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] It can also be used to perform basic variable assignment within an imperative-style block.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Any collection with a proper append is already a monoid, but it turns out that `List` is not the only collection that also has a well-defined join and qualifies as a monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] As already mentioned, pure code should not have unmanaged side effects, but that does not preclude a program from *explicitly* describing and managing effects.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] This idea is central to Haskell's **IO monad**, where an object of type `IO a` can be seen as describing an action to be performed in the world, optionally providing information about the world of type `a`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] An action that provides no information about the world has the type `IO ()`, "providing" the dummy value `()`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] When a programmer binds an `IO` value to a function, the function computes the next action to be performed based on the information about the world provided by the previous action (input from users, files, etc.).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Most significantly, because the value of the IO monad can only be bound to a function that computes another IO monad, the bind function imposes a discipline of a sequence of actions where the result of an action can only be provided to a function that will compute the next action to perform.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] This means that actions which do not need to be performed never are, and actions that do need to be performed have a well defined sequence.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] For example, Haskell has several functions for acting on the wider file system, including one that checks whether a file exists and another that deletes a file.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] The first is interested in whether a given file really exists, and as a result, outputs a Boolean value within the `IO` monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] The second function, on the other hand, is only concerned with acting on the file system so the `IO` container it outputs is empty.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Another common situation is keeping a log file or otherwise reporting a program's progress.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Sometimes, a programmer may want to log even more specific, technical data for later profiling or debugging.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] The **Writer monad** can handle these tasks by generating auxiliary output that accumulates step-by-step.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] To show how the monad pattern is not restricted to primarily functional languages, this example implements a `Writer` monad in Java, stored in a class representing the `Writer` monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] An environment monad (also called a *reader monad* and a *function monad*) allows a computation to depend on values from a shared environment.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] The monad type constructor maps a type T to functions of type *E* → *T*, where E is the type of the shared environment.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] The ask operation is used to retrieve the current context, while local executes a computation in a modified subcontext.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] As in a state monad, computations in the environment monad may be invoked by simply providing an environment value and applying it to an instance of the monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Formally, a value in an environment monad is equivalent to a function with an additional, anonymous argument; return and bind are equivalent to the K and S combinators, respectively, in the SKI combinator calculus.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] A state monad allows a programmer to attach state information of any type to a calculation.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Given any value type, the corresponding type in the state monad is a function which accepts a state, then outputs a new state (of type `s`) along with a return value (of type `t`).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] This is similar to an environment monad, except that it also returns a new state, and thus allows modeling a *mutable* environment.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Note that this monad takes a type parameter, the type of the state information.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] do-blocks in a state monad are sequences of operations that can examine and update the state data.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Informally, a state monad of state type S maps the type of return values T into functions of type S → T × S {\displaystyle S\rightarrow T\times S} ({\displaystyle S\rightarrow T\times S}), where S is the underlying state.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] From the category theory point of view, a state monad is derived from the adjunction between the product functor and the exponential functor, which exists in any cartesian closed category by definition.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] A continuation monad with return type R maps type T into functions of type ( T → R ) → R {\displaystyle \left(T\rightarrow R\right)\rightarrow R} ({\displaystyle \left(T\rightarrow R\right)\rightarrow R}).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] It is used to model continuation-passing style.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] That is, both functions take in an integer and return another integer.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Where the result is the result of `foo` applied to the result of `bar` applied to `x`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] But suppose we are debugging our program, and we would like to add logging messages to `foo` and `bar`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] So that both functions return a tuple, with the result of the application as the integer, and a logging message with information about the applied function and all the previously applied functions as the string.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Unfortunately, this means we can no longer compose `foo` and `bar`, as their input type `int` is not compatible with their output type `int * string`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] And although we can again gain composability by modifying the types of each function to be `int * string -> int * string`, this would require us to add boilerplate code to each function to extract the integer from the tuple, which would get tedious as the number of such functions increases.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] `bind` takes in an integer and string tuple, then takes in a function (like `foo`) that maps from an integer to an integer and string tuple.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Its output is an integer and string tuple, which is the result of applying the input function to the integer within the input integer and string tuple.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] In this way, we only need to write boilerplate code to extract the integer from the tuple once, in `bind`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Now we have regained some composability.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Where `(x,s)` is an integer and string tuple.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] So that `t >>= f` is the same as `bind t f`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Finally, we define a new function to avoid writing `(x, "")` every time we wish to create an empty logging message, where `""` is the empty string.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Which wraps `x` in the tuple described above.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] That allows us to more easily log the effects of `bar` and `foo` on `x`.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] `int * string` denotes a pseudo-coded **monadic value**.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] `bind` and `return` are analogous to the corresponding functions of the same name.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] In fact, `int * string`, `bind`, and `return` form a monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] An **additive monad** is a monad endowed with an additional closed, associative, binary operator **mplus** and an identity element under mplus, called **mzero**.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] The `Maybe` monad can be considered additive, with `Nothing` as mzero and a variation on the OR operator as mplus.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] `List` is also an additive monad, with the empty list `[]` acting as mzero and the concatenation operator `++` as mplus.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Intuitively, mzero represents a monadic wrapper with no value from an underlying type, but is also considered a "zero" (rather than a "one") since it acts as an absorber for bind, returning mzero whenever bound to a monadic function.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] This property is two-sided, and bind will also return mzero when any value is bound to a monadic zero function.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] In category-theoretic terms, an additive monad qualifies once as a monoid over monadic functions with bind (as all monads do), and again over monadic values via mplus.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Sometimes, the general outline of a monad may be useful, but no simple pattern recommends one monad or another.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] This is where a **free monad** comes in; as a free object in the category of monads, it can represent monadic structure without any specific constraints beyond the monad laws themselves.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Just as a free monoid concatenates elements without evaluation, a free monad allows chaining computations with markers to satisfy the type system, but otherwise imposes no deeper semantics itself.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] For example, by working entirely through the `Just` and `Nothing` markers, the `Maybe` monad is in fact a free monad.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] The `List` monad, on the other hand, is not a free monad since it brings extra, specific facts about lists (like append) into its definition.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Free monads, however, are *not* restricted to a linked-list like in this example, and can be built around other structures like trees.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Using free monads intentionally may seem impractical at first, but their formal nature is particularly well-suited for syntactic problems.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] A free monad can be used to track syntax and type while leaving semantics for later, and has found use in parsers and interpreters as a result.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Others have applied them to more dynamic, operational problems too, such as providing iteratees within a language.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Besides generating monads with extra properties, for any given monad, one can also define a **comonad**.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Conceptually, if monads represent computations built up from underlying values, then comonads can be seen as reductions back down to values.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Monadic code, in a sense, cannot be fully "unpacked"; once a value is wrapped within a monad, it remains quarantined there along with any side-effects (a good thing in purely functional programming).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Sometimes though, a problem is more about consuming contextual data, which comonads can model explicitly.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Technically, a comonad is the categorical dual of a monad, which loosely means that it will have the same required components, only with the direction of the type signatures *reversed*.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] While operations like extend are reversed, however, a comonad does *not* reverse functions it acts on, and consequently, comonads are still functors with map, not cofunctors.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] A simple example is the **Product comonad**, which outputs values based on an input value and shared environment data.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] In fact, the `Product` comonad is just the dual of the `Writer` monad and effectively the same as the `Reader` monad (both discussed below).
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] `Product` and `Reader` differ only in which function signatures they accept, and how they complement those functions by wrapping or unwrapping values.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] A less trivial example is the **Stream comonad**, which can be used to represent data streams and attach filters to the incoming signals with extend.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] In fact, while not as popular as monads, researchers have found comonads particularly useful for stream processing and modeling dataflow programming.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] Due to their strict definitions, however, one cannot simply move objects back and forth between monads and comonads.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming-p02] As an even higher abstraction, arrows can subsume both structures, but finding more granular ways to combine monadic and comonadic code is an active area of research.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming] Informally, a state monad of state type S maps the type of return values T into functions of type $S\rightarrow T\times S$ , where S is the underlying state.
[src:haskell/monad-functional-programming] A continuation monad with return type R maps type T into functions of type $\left(T\rightarrow R\right)\rightarrow R$ .
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] In the previous modules, we introduced and made occasional reference to pattern matching.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Now that we have developed some familiarity with the language, it is time to take a proper, deeper look.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Pattern matching is virtually everywhere.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] At surface level, there are four different patterns involved, two per equation.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] In the `(x:xs)` pattern, `x` and `xs` can be seen as sub-patterns used to match the parts of the list.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Just like `f`, they match anything - though it is evident that if there is a successful match and `x` has type `a`, `xs` will have type `[a]`.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Finally, these considerations imply that `xs` will also match an empty list, and so a one-element list matches `(x:xs)`.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Despite the detailed analysis above, it may seem a little too magical how we break down a list as if we were undoing the effects of the `(:)` operator.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Be careful: this process will not work with any arbitrary operator.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] The function `(++)` is not allowed in patterns.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] In fact, most other functions that act on lists are similarly prohibited from pattern matching.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] In one word, *constructors* – the functions used to build values of algebraic data types.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Here `Bar` and `Baz` are constructors for the type `Foo`.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] This is exactly like `showAnniversary` and `showDate` in the Type declarations module.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] The `(Date y m d)` pattern in the left-hand side of the `showDate` definition matches a `Date` (built with the `Date` constructor) and binds the variables `y`, `m` and `d` to the contents of the `Date` value.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] As for lists, they are no different from `data`-defined algebraic data types as far as pattern matching is concerned.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] So the empty list, `[]` and the `(:)` function are constructors of the list datatype, and so you can pattern match with them.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] `[]` takes no arguments, and therefore no variables can be bound when it is used for pattern matching.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] `(:)` takes two arguments, the list head and tail, which may then have variables bound to them when the pattern is recognized.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] (This might seem odd if you slipped into thinking that : adds to a list.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] The first pattern will match any list with at least three elements.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] The catch-all second definition provides a reasonable default when lists fail to match the main pattern, and thus prevents runtime crashes due to pattern match failure.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] From the fact that we *could* write a `dropThree` function with bare pattern matching it doesn't follow that we *should* do so!
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Even though the solution is simple, it is still a waste of effort to code something this specific when we could just use Prelude and settle it with `drop 3 xs` instead.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Analogous considerations are valid for tuples.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Our access to their components via pattern matching...
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] ... is granted by the existence of tuple constructors.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] For pairs, the constructor is the comma operator, `(,)`; for larger tuples there are `(,,)`; `(,,,)` and so on.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] These operators are slightly unusual in that we can't use them infix in the regular way; so `5 , 3` is not a valid way to write `(5, 3)`.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] All of them, however, can be used prefix, which is occasionally useful.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] is performing pattern matching as well, matching the argument of `f` with the `Int` literals 0, 1 and 2, and finally with `_` .
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] In general, numeric and character literals can be used in pattern matching on their own as well as together with constructor patterns.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] will evaluate to False for the [0] list, to True if the list has 0 as first element and a non-empty tail and to False in all other cases.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Also, lists with literal elements like [1,2,3], or even "abc" (which is equivalent to ['a','b','c']) can be used for pattern matching as well, since these forms are only syntactic sugar for the (:) constructor.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Sometimes, when matching a sub-pattern within a value, it may be useful to bind a name to the whole value being matched.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] As-patterns allow exactly this: they are of the form *`var@pattern`* and have the additional effect to bind the name `var` to the whole value being matched by `pattern`.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] `contrivedMap` passes to the parameter function `f` not only `x` but also the undivided list used as argument of each recursive call.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] The function `g` does not have to be changed if we modify the number or the type of elements of the constructors `Bar` or `Baz`.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] There are further advantages to using record syntax which we will cover in more details in the Named fields section of the More on datatypes chapter.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] The short answer is that *wherever you can bind variables, you can pattern match*.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Let us have a glance at such places we have seen before; a few more will be introduced in the following chapters.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] The most obvious use case is the left-hand side of function definition equations, which were the subject of our examples so far.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] In the `map` definition we're doing pattern matching on the left hand side of both equations, and also binding variables on the second one.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Both `let` and `where` are ways of doing local variable bindings.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] As such, you can also use pattern matching in them.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Here, `x` will be bound to the first element of `map ((*) 2) [1,2,3]`.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] It is clear, however, that this syntax permits only one pattern (or one for each argument in the case of a multi-argument lambda abstraction).
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] After the `|` in list comprehensions you can pattern match.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] This is actually extremely useful, and adds a lot to the expressiveness of comprehensions.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Let's see how that works with a slightly more sophisticated example.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] It is typically used to hold values resulting from an operation which may or may not succeed; if the operation succeeds, the `Just` constructor is used and the value is passed to it; otherwise `Nothing` is used.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] The utility function `catMaybes` (which is available from Data.Maybe library module) takes a list of Maybes (which may contain both "Just" and "Nothing" Maybes), and retrieves the contained values by filtering out the `Nothing` values and getting rid of the `Just` wrappers of the `Just x`.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Another nice thing about using a list comprehension for this task is that if the pattern match fails (that is, it meets a Nothing) it just moves on to the next element in `ms`, thus avoiding the need of explicitly handling constructors we are not interested in with alternate function definitions.
[src:haskell/pattern-matching] Furthermore, the `let` bindings in `do` blocks are, as far as pattern matching is concerned, just the same as the "real" let expressions.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] There is a certain mystique about monads, and even about the word "monad" itself.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] While one of our goals of this set of chapters is removing the shroud of mystery that is often wrapped around them, it is not difficult to understand how it comes about.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Monads are very useful in Haskell, but the concept is often difficult to grasp at first.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Since monads have so many applications, people often explain them from a particular point of view, which can derail your efforts towards understanding them in their full glory.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Historically, monads were introduced into Haskell to perform input and output – that is, I/O operations of the sort we dealt with in the Simple input and output chapter and the prologue to this unit.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] A predetermined execution order is crucial for things like reading and writing files, and monadic operations lend themselves naturally to sequencing.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] However, monads are by no means limited to input and output.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] They can be used to provide a whole range of features, such as exceptions, state, non-determinism, continuations, coroutines, and more.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In fact, thanks to the versatility of monads, none of these constructs needed to be built into Haskell as a language; rather, they are defined by the standard libraries.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In the Prologue chapter, we began with an example and used it to steadily introduce several new ideas.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Here, we will do it the other way around, starting with a definition of monad and, from that, building connections with what we already know.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] and are required to obey three laws that will be explained later on.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] For a concrete example, take the `Maybe` monad.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] `Maybe` is the monad, and `return` brings a value into it by wrapping it with `Just`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] As for `(>>=)`, it takes a `m :: Maybe a` value and a `g :: a -> Maybe b` function.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] If `m` is `Nothing`, there is nothing to do and the result is `Nothing`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Otherwise, in the `Just x` case, `g` is applied to `x`, the underlying value wrapped in `Just`, to give a `Maybe b` result.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Note that this result may or may not be `Nothing`, depending on what `g` does to `x`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] To sum it all up, if there is an *underlying value* of type `a` in `m`, we apply `g` to it, which brings the underlying value back into the `Maybe` monad.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The key first step to understand how `return` and `(>>=)` work is tracking which values and arguments are monadic and which ones aren't.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] As in so many other cases, type signatures are our guide to the process.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] These look up the name of someone's father or mother.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In case our database is missing some relevant information, `Maybe` allows us to return a `Nothing` value to indicate that the lookup failed, rather than crashing the program.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Let's combine our functions to query various grandparents.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Every single query might fail by returning `Nothing` and the whole function must fail with `Nothing` if that happens.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Clearly there has to be a better way to write that instead of repeating the case of `Nothing` again and again!
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Indeed, that's what the `Maybe` monad is set out to do.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] While these nested lambda expressions may look confusing to you, the thing to take away here is that `(>>=)` releases us from listing all the `Nothing`s, shifting the focus back to the interesting part of the code.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] To be a little more precise: The result of `father p` is a monadic value (in this case, either `Just dad` or `Nothing`, depending on whether `p`'s father is in the database).
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] As the `father` function takes a regular (non-monadic) value, the `(>>=)` feeds `p`'s `dad` to it *as a non-monadic* value.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The result of `father dad` is then monadic again, and the process continues.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] So, `(>>=)` helps us pass non-monadic values to functions without actually leaving a monad.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In the case of the `Maybe` monad, the monadic aspect is the uncertainty about whether a value will be found.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In Haskell, the `Monad` type class is used to implement monads.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] It is provided by the Control.Monad module and included in the Prelude.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Aside from return and bind, there are two additional methods, `(>>)` and `fail`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Both of them have default implementations, and so you don't need to provide them when writing an instance.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] `(>>)` sequences two monadic actions when the second action does not involve the result of the first, which is a common scenario for monads such as `IO`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The function `fail` handles pattern match failures in `do` notation.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] It's an unfortunate technical necessity and doesn't really have anything to do with monads.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] You are advised not to call `fail` directly in your code.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] An important thing to note is that `Applicative` is a superclass of `Monad`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] That has a few consequences worth highlighting.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] First of all, every `Monad` is also a `Functor` and an `Applicative`, and so `fmap`, `pure`, `(<*>)` can all be used with monads.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Secondly, actually writing a `Monad` instance also requires providing `Functor` and `Applicative` instances.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] We will discuss ways of doing that later in this chapter.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Thirdly, if you have worked through the Prologue, the types and roles of `return` and `(>>)` should look familiar...
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The only difference between the types of `(*>)` and `(>>)` is that the constraint changes from `Applicative` to `Monad`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In fact, that is the only difference between the methods: if you are dealing with a `Monad` you can always replace `(*>)` and `(>>)`, and vice-versa.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The same goes for `pure`/`return` – in fact, it is not even necessary to implement `return` if there is an independent definition of `pure` in the `Applicative` instance, as `return = pure` is provided as a default definition of `return`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] We have seen how `(>>=)` and `return` are very handy for removing boilerplate code that crops up when using `Maybe`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] That, however, is not enough to justify why monads matter so much.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Our next step towards that will be rewriting the two-grandfathers function in a quite different-looking style: using `do` notation with explicit braces and semicolons.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] If this looks like a code snippet in an imperative programming language to you, that's because it *is*.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In particular, this imperative language supports *exceptions* : `father` and `mother` are functions that might fail to produce results, raising an exception instead; when that happens, the whole `do`-block will *fail*, i.e. terminate with an exception (meaning, evaluate to `Nothing`, here).
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In other words, the expression `father p`, which has type `Maybe Person`, is interpreted as a statement in an imperative *language* that returns a `Person` as the result, or fails.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] This is true for all monads: a value of type `M a` is interpreted as a *statement* in an imperative language `M` that returns a value of type `a` as its result; the semantics of this language are determined by the monad `M`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Under this interpretation, the *then* operator `(>>)` is simply an implementation of the semicolon, and `(>>=)` of the semicolon and assignment (binding) of the result of a previous computational step.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In case of functions, `&` and `id` are trivial; in case of a monad, `>>=` and `return` are substantial.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The `&` operator combines two pure *calculations*, `foo` and `id (x + 3)`, while creating a new binding for the variable `x` to hold `foo`'s *value*, making `x` available to the second calculational step, `id (x + 3)`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The bind operator `>>=` combines two *computational* steps, `foo` and `return (x + 3)`, in a manner particular to the monad `M`, while creating a new binding for the variable `x` to hold `foo`'s *result*, making `x` available to the next computational step, `return (x + 3)`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] In the particular case of `Maybe`, if `foo` will fail to produce a result, the second step is skipped and the whole combined computation will fail right away as well.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The function `return` lifts a plain value `a` to `M a`, a statement in the imperative language `M`, which statement, when executed / run, will result in the value `a` without any additional effects particular to `M`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] This is ensured by Monad Laws, `foo >>= return === foo` and `return x >>= k === k x`; see below.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The fact that `(>>=)`, and therefore `Monad`, lies behind the left arrows in `do`-blocks explains why we were not able to explain them in the Prologue, when we only knew about `Functor` and `Applicative`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] `Applicative` would be enough to provide some, but not all, of the functionality of a `do`-block.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Different semantics of the imperative language correspond to different monads.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The following table shows the classic selection that every Haskell programmer should know.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] If the idea behind monads is still unclear to you, studying each of the examples in the following chapters will not only give you a well-rounded toolbox but also help you understand the common abstraction behind them.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Furthermore, these different semantics need not occur in isolation.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] As we will see in a few chapters, it is possible to mix and match them by using monad transformers to combine the semantics of multiple monads in a single monad.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The behavior of `return` is specified by the left and right unit laws.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] They state that `return` doesn't perform any computation, it just collects values.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] where `(>=>)` is the *monad composition operator*, a close analogue of the function composition operator `(.)`, only with flipped arguments.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] There is also `(<=<)`, which is flipped version of `(>=>)`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] When using it, the order of composition matches that of `(.)`, so that in `(f <=< g)` `g` comes first.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Monads originally come from a branch of mathematics called Category Theory.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Fortunately, it is entirely unnecessary to understand category theory in order to understand and use monads in Haskell.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The definition of monads in Category Theory actually uses a slightly different presentation.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Translated into Haskell, this presentation gives an alternative yet equivalent definition of a monad, which can give us some additional insight on the `Monad` class.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] So far, we have defined monads in terms of `(>>=)` and `return`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] For the purposes of this discussion, we will use the functors-as-containers metaphor discussed in the chapter on the functor class.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] According to it, a functor `M` can be thought of as container, so that `M a` "contains" values of type `a`, with a corresponding mapping function, i.e.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] `fmap`, that allows functions to be applied to values inside it.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Earlier, we pointed out that every `Monad` is an `Applicative`, and therefore also a `Functor`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] One of the consequences of that was `return` and `(>>)` being monad-only versions of `pure` and `(*>)` respectively.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] For one, `Control.Monad` defines `liftM`, a function with a strangely familiar type signature...
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] As you might suspect, `liftM` is merely `fmap` implemented with `(>>=)` and `return`, just as we have done in the previous section.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] `liftM` and `fmap` are therefore interchangeable.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Analogously to the other cases, `ap` is a monad-only version of `(<*>)`.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] There are quite a few more examples of `Applicative` functions that have versions *specialised* to `Monad` in `Control.Monad` and other base library modules.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] Their existence is primarily due to historical reasons: several years went by between the introductions of `Monad` and `Applicative` in Haskell, and it took an even longer time for `Applicative` to become a superclass of `Monad`, thus making usage of the specialised variants optional.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] While following the next few chapters, you will likely want to write instances of `Monad` and try them out, be it to run the examples in the book or to do other experiments you might think of.
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] However, writing the instances in the manner shown above requires implementing `pure` and `(<*>)`, which is not a comfortable task at this point of the book as we haven't covered the `Applicative` laws yet (we will only do so at the applicative functors chapter).
[src:haskell/understanding-monads] The examples and exercises in this initial series of chapters about monads will not demand writing `Applicative` instances, and so you can use this workaround until we discuss `Applicative` in detail.
