[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Of course, that's only practical for short calculations.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] For longer calculations and for writing Haskell programs, we want to keep track of intermediate results.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We can store intermediate results by assigning them names.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] When a program runs, each variable is substituted for the *value* to which it refers.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] That is the approximate area of a circle with radius `5`, according to the formula $A=\pi r^{2}$ .
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Of course, it is cumbersome to type in the digits of $\pi \approx 3.141592653$ , or even to remember more than the first few.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Programming helps us avoid mindless repetition and rote memorization by delegating these tasks to a machine.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] That way, our minds stay free to deal with more interesting ideas.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] For the present case, Haskell already includes a variable named `pi` that stores over a dozen digits of $\pi$ for us.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Note that the variable `pi` and its value, `3.141592653589793`, can be used interchangeably in calculations.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Beyond momentary operations in GHCi, you will save your code in Haskell source files (basically plain text) with the extension `.hs`.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Work with these files using a text editor appropriate for coding (see the Wikipedia article on text editors).
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Proper source code editors will provide *syntax highlighting*, which colors the code in relevant ways to make reading and understanding easier.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Vim and Emacs are popular choices among Haskell programmers, but have a bit of a learning curve to be able to fully benefit from their features.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Visual Studio Code is also popular among Haskell programmers and is easier for beginners to use.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] To keep things tidy, create a directory (i.e. a folder) in your computer to save the Haskell files you will create while doing the exercises in this book.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Call the directory something like `HaskellWikibook`.
