[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We will usually want to use saved source files.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Besides the working code itself, source files may contain text *comments*.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] In Haskell there are two types of comment.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] In this case, `x` and `y` are defined in actual Haskell code, but `z` is not.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We use comments for explaining parts of a program or making other notes in context.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Beware of comment overuse as too many comments can make programs harder to read.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Also, we must carefully update comments whenever we change the corresponding code.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Outdated comments can cause significant confusion.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Readers familiar with imperative programming will notice that variables in Haskell seem quite different from variables in languages like C.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] If you have no programming experience, you could skip this section, but it will help you understand the general situation when encountering the many cases (most Haskell textbooks, for example) where people discuss Haskell in reference to other programming languages.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] An imperative programmer may read this as first setting `r = 5` and then changing it to `r = 2`.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] In Haskell, however, the compiler will respond to the code above with an error: "multiple declarations of `r`".
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Within a given scope, a variable in Haskell gets defined only once and cannot change.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] The variables in Haskell seem almost *invariable*, but they work like variables in mathematics.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] In a math classroom, you never see a variable change its value within a single problem.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] In precise terms, Haskell variables are *immutable*.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] They vary only based on the data we enter into a program.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We can't define `r` two ways in the same code, but we could change the value by changing the file.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We can change `r` in the one place where it is defined, and that will automatically update the value of all the rest of the code that uses the `r` variable.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Real-world Haskell programs work by leaving *some* variables unspecified in the code.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] The values then get defined when the program gets data from an external file, a database, or user input.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] For now, however, we will stick to defining variables internally.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We will cover interaction with external data in later chapters.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Instead of "incrementing the variable `r`" (i.e. updating the value in memory), this Haskell code is a recursive definition of `r` (i.e. defining it in terms of itself).
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We will explain recursion in detail later on.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] For this specific case, if `r` had been defined with any value beforehand, then `r = r + 1` in Haskell would bring an error message.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] `r = r + 1` is akin to saying, in a mathematical context, that $5=5+1$ , which is plainly wrong.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Because their values do not change within a program, variables can be defined in any order.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] In Haskell, there is no notion of "`x` being declared before `y`" or the other way around.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Of course, using `y` will still require a value for `x`, but this is unimportant until you need a specific numeric value.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Changing our program every time we want to calculate the area of new circle is both tedious and limited to one circle at a time.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Of course, to eliminate this mindless repetition, we would prefer to have simply one *function* for area and then apply it to different radii.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] A *function* takes an *argument* value (or *parameter*) and gives a result value (essentially the same as in mathematical functions).
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Defining functions in Haskell is like defining a variable, except that we take note of the function argument that we put on the left hand side of the equals sign.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Look closely at the syntax: the function name comes first (`area` in our example), followed by a space and then the argument (`r` in the example).
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Following the `=` sign, the *function definition* is a formula that uses the argument in context with other already defined terms.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Now, we can plug in different values for the argument in a *call* to the function.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Thus, we can *call* this function with different radii to calculate the area of any circle.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] In mathematics, the argument is enclosed between parentheses, as in $A(5)=78.54$ or $A(3)=28.27$ .
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Many programming languages likewise surround arguments with parentheses, as in `max(2, 3)`.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] But Haskell omits parentheses around a list of arguments (as well as commas between them): `max 2 3`.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We still use parentheses for grouping *expressions* (any code that gives a value) that must be evaluated together.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Note that Haskell functions take *precedence* over all other operators such as `+` and `*`, in the same way that, for instance, multiplication is done before addition in mathematics.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] What exactly happens when you enter an expression into GHCi?
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] After you press the enter key, GHCi will *evaluate* the expression you have given.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] That means it will replace each function with its definition and calculate the results until a single value remains.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] As this shows, to *apply* or *call* a function means to replace the left-hand side of its definition by its right-hand side.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] When using GHCi, the results of a function call will then show on the screen.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Functions can also take more than one argument.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] As you can see, multiple arguments are separated by spaces.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] That's also why you sometimes have to use parentheses to group expressions.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] That would apply a function named `double` to the two arguments `double` and `x`.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Note that *functions can be arguments to other functions* (you will see why later).
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Arguments are always passed in the order given.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Here, `minus 10 5` evaluates to `10 - 5`, but `minus 5 10` evaluates to `5 - 10` because the order changes.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Of course, you can use functions that you have already defined to define new functions, just like you can use the predefined functions like addition `(+)` or multiplication `(*)` (operators are defined as functions in Haskell).
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] After all, a square is just a rectangle with equal sides.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] When defining a function, we sometimes want to define intermediate results that are *local* to the function.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] The variable `s` is half the perimeter of the triangle and it would be tedious to write it out four times in the argument of the square root function `sqrt`.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Simply writing the definitions in sequence does not work...
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] ... because the variables `a`, `b`, `c` are only available in the right-hand side of the function `heron`, but the definition of `s` as written here is not part of the right-hand side of `heron`.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] To make it part of the right-hand side, we use the `where` keyword.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Note that both the `where` and the local definitions are *indented* by 4 spaces, to distinguish them from subsequent definitions.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] If you look closely at the previous example, you'll notice that we have used the variable names `a`, `b`, `c` twice, once for each of the two area functions.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] It would have been an unpleasant surprise to return `0` for the area because of the earlier `let r = 0` definition getting in the way.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] That does not happen because when you defined `r` the second time you are talking about a *different* `r`.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] This may seem confusing, but consider how many people have the name John, and yet for any context with only one John, we can talk about "John" with no confusion.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Programming has a notion similar to context, called *scope*.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We will not explain the technicalities behind scope right now.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Just keep in mind that the value of a parameter is strictly what you pass in when you call the function, regardless of what the variable was called in the function's definition.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] That said, appropriately unique names for variables do make the code easier for human readers to understand.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] Functions can accept more than one parameter.
[src:haskell/variables-and-functions] We also learned about non-code text comments within a source file.
